TWOPET_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>2 Peter is widely recognized as a <em>testament</em> or <em>farewell discourse</em> — a literary form well-established in Second Temple Judaism (Testament of Moses, Testament of the Twelve Patriarchs, Deut 31–33, John 13–17) in which a departing leader delivers final instructions to his community. The letter's explicit acknowledgment of imminent death (vv. 14-15) confirms this genre. Testaments typically review past history, warn of coming apostasy, exhort to fidelity, and predict the future — all features present in 2 Peter. The pseudonymous attribution debate notwithstanding, the letter presents itself as Petrine final testimony, and the testament form signals that every word carries end-of-life gravity.</p>",

    "2": "<p>'Knowledge of God and of Jesus our Lord' — <em>epignōsis</em> appears five times in 2 Peter (1:2, 3, 8; 2:20; 3:18), far more densely than in any other NT letter. In Second Temple Judaism <em>epignōsis</em> (full, experiential knowledge) was distinguished from <em>gnōsis</em> (bare intellectual knowledge); it implies covenant participation, not mere information. The emphasis on true versus false knowledge is the epistemological battleground of the letter: the false teachers claim wisdom (2:12) while lacking the genuine <em>epignōsis</em> that produces holy character. Grace and peace multiplied 'through knowledge' signals that experiential knowledge of Christ is the medium of divine blessing.</p>",

    "3": "<p>'His divine power has given us everything we need for life and godliness through our knowledge of him who called us by his own glory and goodness.' The phrase 'divine power' (<em>theias dynameōs</em>) and the appeal to glory and virtue/goodness (<em>aretēs</em>) reflect Hellenistic-Jewish appropriation of Greek philosophical vocabulary. <em>Aretē</em> (excellence, virtue) was the Stoic and Platonic pinnacle of human flourishing; 2 Peter applies it to God himself, claiming that God's own excellence is the means and ground of the community's godly life. The letter consistently translates Jewish theological content into categories familiar to Greco-Roman philosophy without surrendering the Jewish-Christian substance.</p>",

    "4": "<p>'Partakers of the divine nature' (<em>theias koinōnoi physeōs</em>) — this is the most explicitly Hellenistic formulation in the NT. Greek philosophy, particularly Middle Platonism and Stoicism, spoke of the goal of human life as <em>homoiōsis theō</em> (likeness to God) through participation in the divine logos or nous. 2 Peter appropriates this vocabulary for Jewish-Christian ends: the divine nature shared is not absorption into deity (as in Neoplatonism) but moral participation through promise — the same promises about resurrection, the Spirit, and the new creation that ground all NT ethics. The corruption (<em>phthoras</em>) to be escaped is the moral corruption of <em>epithymia</em> (desire), not the material world.</p>",

    "5": "<p>The virtue-chain (<em>sorites</em>) of vv. 5-7 belongs to a well-established Hellenistic literary form: the chain-argument that links virtues progressively, each building on the prior, toward a culminating virtue (here, love). Stoic diatribe used similar lists to demonstrate the systematic nature of virtue. The Hellenistic-Jewish philosophical tradition (Philo of Alexandria, Wisdom of Solomon) adapted the genre for Jewish ethics. 2 Peter's chain begins with faith and ends with love, situating distinctly Christian virtues (faith, brotherly affection, agapē) within a framework that Greco-Roman philosophical readers would find immediately recognizable as a discourse on the <em>telos</em> (goal) of human development.</p>",

    "6": "<p><em>Enkrateia</em> (self-control) was the Stoic cardinal virtue governing the mastery of passions — Epictetus and Marcus Aurelius identified it as the foundation of philosophical life. In the context of 2 Peter, where the false teachers are characterized precisely by their lack of self-mastery ('following the corrupt desire of the flesh,' 2:10; 'eyes full of adultery,' 2:14), the virtue-chain's inclusion of <em>enkrateia</em> is polemically pointed. The false teachers who claim philosophical or spiritual sophistication lack the most basic philosophical prerequisite. Perseverance (<em>hypomonē</em>) adds the Jewish-covenantal virtue to the Hellenistic list: patience-under-trial as the distinctive mark of the people of God.</p>",

    "7": "<p>The culmination of the virtue chain in <em>agapē</em> (love) follows the Pauline prioritization (1 Cor 13: 'the greatest of these is love') but also the wisdom tradition's identification of love as the fulfillment of Torah (Lev 19:18, cited throughout the NT). <em>Philadelphia</em> (brotherly affection) belongs to the Greek world of kinship-based loyalty; <em>agapē</em> is the specifically Christian expansion of that loyalty beyond the in-group. The sequence — faith, virtue, knowledge, self-control, perseverance, godliness, brotherly affection, love — traces the movement from initial trust to the comprehensive outward orientation of love.</p>",

    "8": "<p>The warning about being 'ineffective and unproductive' (<em>argous kai akarpous</em>) in knowledge employs agricultural metaphors familiar from both wisdom literature and the teaching of Jesus (the Parable of the Sower, John 15:1-8). The Second Temple assumption was that genuine knowledge of God produces observable moral fruit; a claim to spiritual knowledge that generates no practical holiness was self-refuting. This mirrors the critique of the false teachers in ch. 2, whose knowledge (v. 20: 'escaped the corruption of the world by knowing the Lord') did not produce the fruit of transformed character and led them back into the very vices they had escaped.</p>",

    "9": "<p>'Blind' and 'shortsighted' (<em>typhlos, myōpazōn</em>) — blindness is a stock OT image for spiritual insensibility: Isaiah's 'blind servant' (Isa 42:18-20), Jer 5:21 ('eyes but they do not see'), and the prophetic tradition of spiritual blindness as covenant unfaithfulness. Jesus applies the image to Pharisees who claimed to see (John 9:40-41). The 'forgetting' of baptismal cleansing from sins is significant: in the Second Temple period, forgetting the covenant mercies was the root failure of apostasy (Deut 8:11-20; Ps 106). The false teachers of ch. 2 represent this forgetfulness systematized into lifestyle.</p>",

    "10": "<p>'Confirm your calling and election' (<em>bebaian hymon tēn klēsin kai eklogēn poieisthai</em>) — <em>klēsis</em> (calling) and <em>eklogē</em> (election) are the twin Pauline terms for the divine initiative in salvation (Rom 8:28-30; 9:11; Eph 1:4-5). The exhortation to 'make it sure/firm' does not undermine divine election but reflects the Second Temple Jewish conviction that election is confirmed through the life it produces — that God's choice is visible in the character of the chosen. The Dead Sea Scrolls community (1QS) similarly emphasized that election manifested in strict observance; 2 Peter's concern is with the character-confirmation of election rather than its abstract certainty.</p>",

    "11": "<p>'Rich welcome into the eternal kingdom' (<em>plousios epichorēgēthēsetai</em>) — <em>epichorēgeō</em> means to provide lavishly; the same root is used in v. 5 ('make every effort to supplement your faith'). The lavish provision metaphor belongs to the patronage culture of the Roman world: wealthy patrons provided spectacularly for those in their household. The eternal kingdom of Jesus Christ as the eschatological household of divine patronage reverses the social calculus of vv. 5-7: the virtue-building investment in the present age is rewarded by the patron's lavish welcome at the gate.</p>",

    "12": "<p>Peter's commitment to repetition and reminding ('I will always remind you... even though you know them') reflects the Jewish pedagogical tradition of <em>hazkarah</em> (memorial reminder): rehearsing foundational truths not because the audience is ignorant but because the act of recollection is itself formative. Deuteronomy embodies this pattern — Moses repeatedly rehearses the Sinai events for a generation that was not there. The homily and synagogue tradition carried this into Second Temple Judaism: liturgical memory of the Exodus (Passover), the giving of Torah (Shavuot), and divine rescue was constitutive of Jewish identity.</p>",

    "13": "<p>'In the tent of this body' (<em>skēnōma</em>) — the body-as-tent image appears in Paul (2 Cor 5:1-4: 'if this earthly tent we live in is destroyed, we have a building from God') and here with the same implication: temporary, mortal, awaiting eschatological transformation. The tent-tabernacle imagery carries exodus freight: Israel lived in tents in the wilderness, and the Tabernacle was the tent of divine dwelling. The human body as temporary dwelling is the foil for the permanent resurrection body and the eternal kingdom of v. 11. Peter's tent-language signals he stands in the same theological tradition as Paul.</p>",

    "14": "<p>'As our Lord Jesus Christ has made clear to me' — the reference is to John 21:18-19, where the risen Jesus predicted Peter's manner of death ('when you are old you will stretch out your hands, and another will dress you and carry you where you do not want to go'). This creates an explicit link between 2 Peter and the Johannine tradition. The foreknowledge of martyrdom by divine revelation is a prophetic convention: the prophets sometimes received anticipatory knowledge of their own death (Isa 8:19-22; Jer 20:7-18). For Peter, it confirms the letter's testimony: his eyewitness authority (vv. 16-18) is validated by the same Lord who foretold his end.</p>",

    "15": "<p>'After my departure' (<em>meta tēn emēn exodon</em>) — <em>exodos</em> (departure, lit. 'going out') was used in Jewish tradition for Moses's death (Wis 7:6; cf. Luke 9:31: the Transfiguration conversation about the 'exodus' Jesus was about to accomplish in Jerusalem). By using <em>exodos</em> for his own death, Peter may consciously invoke the Moses-departure typology: as Moses left the Torah-covenant as his permanent legacy, Peter leaves this letter. The testament genre (see v. 1 note) regularly positioned the dying leader as Moses-figure. The concern for post-Petrine memory is a concern for community cohesion after the apostolic generation.</p>",

    "16": "<p>'Cleverly devised myths' (<em>sesophismenois mythois</em>) — <em>mythos</em> in Greek philosophical tradition (from Plato onward) meant a story that was illustrative but not factually historical, in contrast to <em>logos</em> (reasoned account) or <em>historia</em> (eyewitness report). The false teachers apparently accused the apostolic message of being myth — a common Hellenistic charge against religious claims. Peter's counter-claim is <em>autopsy</em>: we were eyewitnesses (<em>epoptai</em>). <em>Epoptai</em> was the technical term for initiation into the highest mysteries of the Greek mystery religions (Eleusinian mysteries: <em>epopteia</em> was the final level of initiation). Peter claims a superior and unrepeatable vision: the Transfiguration. The polemical register is unmistakable — apostolic testimony beats mystery-religion initiation.</p>",

    "17": "<p>The Transfiguration on the 'holy mountain' (v. 18) — Peter identifies the Transfiguration (Matt 17:1-8; Mark 9:2-8; Luke 9:28-36) as the unique validating event for apostolic preaching about the Parousia. The 'Majestic Glory' (<em>megaloprepous doxēs</em>) — a divine title that appears in Deut 33:26 LXX and Jewish liturgical texts for the divine glory-cloud (<em>Shekinah</em>). The voice from the cloud ('This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased' — the divine attestation of the Davidic kingship psalm, Ps 2:7, combined with the Servant of YHWH, Isa 42:1) ratified Jesus's messianic identity in the hearing of eyewitnesses.</p>",

    "18": "<p>The 'sacred mountain' (<em>hagiō orei</em>) — in Second Temple tradition, mountains were sites of divine revelation: Sinai (Torah), Zion (Temple), Horeb (Elijah's theopany in 1 Kgs 19). Peter's 'sacred mountain' frames the Transfiguration in the tradition of Mosaic mountain-theophany. Moses received the Torah at Sinai amid divine glory; Peter, James, and John received the apostolic confirmation of Jesus's divine sonship amid a parallel glory-cloud and divine voice. The structural parallel to Sinai is deliberate and theologically loaded: as the Torah came with divine attestation on the holy mountain, the apostolic gospel came with divine attestation on the Transfiguration mountain.</p>",

    "19": "<p>'The prophetic message as something completely reliable, and you will do well to pay attention to it, as to a light shining in a dark place, until the day dawns and the morning star rises in your hearts.' The 'morning star' (<em>phōsphoros</em>) is Venus as it rises before dawn — in Greco-Roman tradition the Lucifer/Phosphorus star that precedes the sun. Jewish eschatology used the dawn as a metaphor for the messianic age (Num 24:17: 'a star will come out of Jacob'; Mal 4:2: 'the sun of righteousness will rise'). The darkness-to-dawn metaphor for the period between the prophets and the Parousia reflects Jewish <em>sapiential</em> tradition: the period between revelations is a dark waiting time; the scripture is the lamp (Ps 119:105) until the promised light arrives.</p>",

    "20": "<p>'No prophecy of Scripture came about by the prophet's own interpretation' (<em>idias epilyseōs</em>) — <em>epilysis</em> (interpretation, solution, unloosing) was used in Greek literary theory for the individual author's private interpretation of dreams or oracles. The claim that Scripture is not of private (<em>idias</em>) origin applies equally to the prophet's composition and the reader's interpretation: neither the prophets themselves nor readers can authorize private, self-serving readings of prophetic texts. This directly challenges the false teachers' hermeneutical practice — 2 Peter 3:16 will accuse them of 'twisting' Scripture to their own ends. The criterion is the Spirit-moved community reading against the private individual's interpretation.</p>",

    "21": "<p>'Prophets, though human, spoke from God as they were carried along by the Holy Spirit' (<em>hypo pneumatos hagiou pheromenoi</em>) — <em>pheromenoi</em> (carried, driven, borne along) is the word used for a ship driven by wind (Acts 27:15, 17). The Spirit-as-wind-driving-prophecy image is consistent with the OT experience: the Spirit comes upon prophets as a wind/breath (<em>ruah</em>), and they speak beyond their own understanding. But <em>pheromenoi</em> does not imply unconscious dictation — prophets remained themselves while being carried. The image is of active human agency sustained and directed by the divine wind, not automatic writing. Jewish tradition (Philo, Josephus, Sibylline Oracles) similarly described prophetic inspiration as divine breath animating the human vessel.</p>"
  },

  "2": {
    "1": "<p>'False prophets among the people... false teachers among you' — 2 Peter 2 is a sustained sustained midrash on the false-prophet tradition of the OT. Deuteronomy 13 and 18 provide the foundational criteria: a prophet is false if their predictions do not come true (Deut 18:21-22) or if they lead people after other gods (Deut 13:1-5). Jeremiah 23 applies these criteria to the professional prophets who prophesied peace when there was no peace. The structural parallel between Israel's false prophets and the false teachers in the community is Peter's way of applying the entire prophetic-tradition critique to the present crisis: these people stand in the line of those who brought Israel to exile.</p>",

    "2": "<p>'Many will follow their depraved conduct and will bring the way of truth into disrepute' (<em>di' hous hē hodos tēs alētheias blasphēmēthēsetai</em>) — <em>hodos</em> (way) as a name for the community and its teaching is rooted in Isa 40:3 ('Prepare the way of the Lord') and was apparently a self-designation of the early church (Acts 9:2; 19:9, 23; 24:14: 'the Way'). The Qumran community also called itself the 'Way' (<em>derekh</em>, 1QS 9:17-18). The community's good name among outsiders was understood in the honor-shame framework of the ancient world: blasphemy of the Way was a social catastrophe that undermined the community's ability to bear witness.</p>",

    "3": "<p>'With fabricated stories they will exploit you' (<em>plastois logois</em>) — <em>plastos</em> (fabricated, molded) is the word for a sculptor's fabrication: the false teachers' words are artificially constructed for the specific purpose of extracting financial benefit. The word appears nowhere else in the NT. In Hellenistic rhetoric, the charge of speaking for pay was a standard philosophical polemic — Socrates was careful to distinguish himself from the sophists who charged fees (Plato's <em>Apology</em>). Jewish tradition similarly distinguished true from false prophecy in part by the motive of gain (Mic 3:11: 'her prophets divine for money').</p>",

    "4": "<p>'God did not spare angels when they sinned, but sent them to hell, putting them in chains of darkness' (<em>Tartaros</em>) — <em>tartaroō</em> (cast into Tartarus) is the only NT use of the Greek mythological term for the deepest underworld prison, the place where the Titans were imprisoned after their rebellion against Zeus (Hesiod, <em>Theogony</em> 720-735). 2 Peter adopts the Greek cosmological term but fills it with the content of 1 Enoch 6-16: the Watchers (sons of God) of Gen 6:1-4 who sinned by cohabiting with human women are imprisoned in darkness awaiting final judgment. This tradition is also presupposed in Jude 6. Jewish and Greco-Roman traditions about imprisoned supernatural beings converge in Peter's argument about cosmic judgment.</p>",

    "5": "<p>'Noah, a preacher of righteousness' (<em>kēryka dikaiosynēs</em>) — the description of Noah as a preacher is not in Genesis; it develops from post-biblical tradition (1 Enoch, Josephus's <em>Antiquities</em> 1.72-74) where Noah warned his contemporaries before the flood. The same tradition appears in the Sibylline Oracles (1.174-195). The title 'preacher of righteousness' parallels John the Baptist's role and anticipates the community's mission: Noah preached to no avail, the flood came anyway, and only his household was saved. The pattern — faithful remnant preserved while judgment falls on the disobedient — is the archetypal template Peter applies to the present crisis of false teaching.</p>",

    "6": "<p>'Condemned the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah by burning them to ashes, and made them an example' (<em>hypodeigma</em>) — the cities as permanent <em>hypodeigma</em> (example, exhibit) of divine judgment reflects the continuing visibility of the destruction in Peter's world: the ashen landscape of the Dead Sea basin was still desolate in the first century, and Jewish and Roman travelers noted the site as a standing warning (Josephus, <em>Jewish War</em> 4.483-485; Tacitus, <em>Histories</em> 5.6-7). Philo of Alexandria similarly used Sodom and Gomorrah as the paradigmatic exhibit of divine retributive justice. The 'burning to ashes' (<em>tephrōsas</em>, NT hapax) may also allude to the continuing sulfurous residue of the landscape.</p>",

    "7": "<p>'Rescued Lot, a righteous man, who was distressed by the depraved conduct of the lawless' — the characterization of Lot as 'righteous' (<em>dikaion</em>) stands in tension with Genesis, where Lot's character is considerably more ambiguous. The positive assessment draws on Jewish interpretive tradition (Wis 10:6: 'Wisdom rescued a righteous man when the ungodly were perishing'; Philo, <em>On Abraham</em> 148). In Second Temple Judaism, Lot's righteousness was developed by contrast with Sodom's corruption — his hospitality (Gen 19:1-3) in a city known for its violation of the hospitality code (inhospitality was a capital crime in many ANE traditions) was taken as evidence of genuine covenant loyalty.</p>",

    "8": "<p>'Living among them day after day, was tormented in his righteous soul by the lawless deeds' — the psych-moral detail of Lot's daily torment (<em>hēmera ex hēmeras psychēn dikaian anomois ergois ebasanizen</em>) belongs to the Stoic-Jewish tradition of the wise man who suffers in corrupt surroundings. Philo and other Hellenistic-Jewish writers used this motif to demonstrate that true righteousness is maintained despite environmental opposition. The word <em>basanizō</em> (tormented) is used elsewhere for demonic affliction and extreme distress (Matt 8:6; Rev 11:10) — living in Sodom was experienced as a form of torture by the righteous soul. This amplification of Lot's distress signals the letter's concern for the community's own experience living among the false teachers.</p>",

    "9": "<p>'The Lord knows how to rescue the godly from trials and to hold the unrighteous for punishment on the day of judgment' — the two-track eschatological pattern (rescue for the righteous, retention for the wicked) reflects the apocalyptic framework developed in 1 Enoch, 4 Ezra, and the Psalms of Solomon: God's final judgment separates the two destinies that have coexisted throughout history. The 'day of judgment' (<em>hēmeras kriseōs</em>) is the technical term for the eschatological assize in Jewish apocalyptic. The argument from the three precedents (angels, flood, Sodom) is a <em>qal va-chomer</em> (from lesser to greater): if God judged these cases, how much more certainly will he judge the present false teachers?</p>",

    "10": "<p>'Those who follow the corrupt desire of the flesh and despise authority. Bold and arrogant, they are not afraid to heap abuse on celestial beings' — the description of the false teachers as those who 'despise lordship' (<em>kyriotētos kataphronountas</em>) and 'blaspheme the glorious ones' (<em>doxas blasphēmountes</em>) appears to describe antinomian teachers who denied the authority of angelic intermediaries over natural processes or moral law. This may reflect contact with early Gnostic-type movements that dismissed the creator-angels and their ethical demands. The 'celestial beings' (<em>doxai</em>, glories) are probably angelic powers — the same <em>archai kai exousiai</em> whose authority Paul affirmed in Col 1:16 and whose defeat he proclaimed in Col 2:15.</p>",

    "11": "<p>'Yet even angels, although they are stronger and more powerful, do not heap abuse on such beings when bringing judgment on them from the Lord' — this likely alludes to the tradition of Michael the archangel's dispute with the devil over Moses's body (Jude 9; perhaps from the lost <em>Testament of Moses</em>). Michael, though more powerful than the devil, refused to pronounce his own condemnation but deferred to the Lord ('the Lord rebuke you'). The contrast in Jude 9 is explicit and provides the interpretive key for 2 Peter's briefer reference: the strongest angelic beings respect their creaturely limits; the false teachers with no such angelic power show no such restraint.</p>",

    "12": "<p>'Like unreasoning animals (<em>aloga zōa</em>), creatures of instinct, born only to be caught and destroyed' — the comparison of the false teachers to <em>aloga zōa</em> (literally 'wordless/irrational animals') draws on Stoic anthropology: Stoics defined the human being as <em>zōon logikon</em> (a rational animal), distinguished from beasts by possession of the <em>logos</em>. To act like an <em>alogon zōon</em> was to abandon what made humans human. Epicurus's opponents charged him with making human beings mere animals driven by pleasure-seeking. 2 Peter's charge against the false teachers uses Stoic anthropology against those who may have invoked Epicurean freedom from constraint: they have become what they rejected — mindless animals.</p>",

    "13": "<p>'Their idea of pleasure is to carouse in broad daylight' (<em>hēdonēn hēgoumenoi tēn en hēmera truphēn</em>) — daytime drinking and feasting was a social marker of the disreputable in both Roman and Jewish culture. Roman authors (Cicero, Sallust) regularly use daytime debauchery as shorthand for dissolute behavior that has abandoned the structuring norms of Roman social life. Jewish tradition (Eccl 10:16-17: 'Woe to you, O land, when your king is a child, and your princes feast in the morning! Happy are you, O land, when your king is of noble birth, and your princes feast at the proper time') similarly treats daytime excess as a mark of corrupt leadership. The false teachers feast at the community's <em>agapē</em> meals while corrupting the very community they exploit.</p>",

    "14": "<p>'With eyes full of adultery' (<em>ophthalmous mestous moichalidos</em>) — the phrase is literally 'eyes full of an adulteress': the false teachers' gaze is perpetually scanning for sexual opportunity, as though they see potential adulterous partners in everyone they look at. The metaphor of the 'evil eye' scanning for prey was common in both Jewish (Prov 6:25: 'Do not desire her beauty in your heart, and do not let her capture you with her eyelashes') and Greco-Roman moral literature. 'Experts in greed' (<em>gegymnasmenēn pleonexias kardian echontes</em>): literally 'having a heart trained (by athletic exercise) in greed' — the <em>gymnazō</em> image inverts the noble purpose of athletic training; these people have disciplined themselves in vice, not virtue.</p>",

    "15": "<p>'The way of Balaam son of Bezer, who loved the wages of wickedness' — Balaam in Numbers 22-24 was hired by Balak king of Moab to curse Israel; when he could not (because God turned his oracles into blessings), he counseled Balak to use Moabite women to lure Israel into idolatry (Num 31:16; Rev 2:14). In Second Temple Judaism, Balaam became the archetypal false prophet who combined prophetic gifts with mercenary motivation (Philo, <em>Life of Moses</em> 1.54; Josephus, <em>Antiquities</em> 4.127). The triad of OT apostasy figures in 2 Peter/Jude — fallen angels, Sodom, Balaam — maps the three modes of false teaching failure: spiritual rebellion, sexual license, and mercenary prophecy.</p>",

    "16": "<p>'He was rebuked for his wrongdoing by a donkey — an animal without speech — who spoke with a human voice and restrained the prophet's madness' — the talking donkey of Num 22:21-35 functioned in Jewish interpretation (Philo, <em>Life of Moses</em> 1.272-274; later rabbinic tradition) as a proof of divine power over nature and an example of how God uses unexpected instruments to restrain human evil. The irony is pointed: the false teacher Balaam, who claimed prophetic gifts, was rebuked by a beast devoid of reason (<em>alogon</em>) — the same category as the false teachers of v. 12. An irrational animal proved wiser than the prophet, just as Peter's community should be wiser than the teachers who claim superior knowledge.</p>",

    "17": "<p>'Springs without water and mists driven by a storm. Blackest darkness is reserved for them' — both images come from the background of Palestinian experience and OT wisdom literature: a waterless spring (cistern that fails, Jer 2:13: 'they have forsaken me, the spring of living water, and have dug out cisterns for themselves, broken cisterns that can hold no water') and a cloud that promises rain but delivers none (Prov 25:14: 'Like clouds and wind without rain is one who boasts of a gift never given'). The false teachers make promises they cannot keep because they have no actual divine resources to offer. The darkness reserved for them frames the judgment that the entire chapter has been building toward.</p>",

    "18": "<p>'They mouth empty, boastful words and, by appealing to the lustful desires of the flesh, they entice people who are just escaping from those who live in error' — the description of the false teachers' rhetorical method: <em>hyperonka mataiotētos</em> (swollen inanities, high-sounding empty words) was a standard charge in Greco-Roman rhetoric against sophists and self-promoters. Dio Chrysostom and Lucian of Samosata both use similar language for those who use inflated rhetoric to impress naive audiences. The specific targeting of those 'just escaping' — new converts still transitionally vulnerable — mirrors what we know of sectarian recruitment practices: new converts, dislocated from their former social networks, are maximally vulnerable to teachers who offer liberation from their old community's moral standards.</p>",

    "19": "<p>'They promise them freedom (<em>eleutherian</em>), while they themselves are slaves of depravity' — the false teachers' claim to freedom echoes Stoic and Cynic philosophical traditions that defined the wise person as truly free regardless of external circumstance. Paul engaged the same vocabulary in Galatia (Gal 5:1, 13: 'For freedom Christ has set us free... do not use your freedom as an opportunity for the flesh'). The Corinthian slogans ('all things are lawful,' 1 Cor 6:12; 10:23) may represent a similar antinomian application of freedom language. Peter's response mirrors Paul's: the freedom that the gospel offers is freedom from sin's domination, not freedom to indulge it; the teachers promising sexual/moral freedom are themselves enslaved.</p>",

    "20": "<p>'If they have escaped the corruption of the world by knowing our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ and are again entangled in it' — the language of 'escaping the corruption of the world' (cf. 1:4) describes baptismal conversion; the 're-entanglement' describes apostasy. The Second Temple and early rabbinic tradition of apostasy (<em>meshumad</em>) carried profound social and theological consequences — it was not merely personal backsliding but an act of social treachery against the covenant community. The teaching context — these are people who 'have known the way of righteousness' (v. 21) — makes their apostasy more culpable than that of the pagans who never knew. The principle follows Amos's 'you only have I known among all the families of the earth; therefore I will punish you for all your iniquities' (Amos 3:2).</p>",

    "21": "<p>'The sacred command that was passed on to them' (<em>tēs paradotheisēs autois hagias entolēs</em>) — <em>paradidōmi</em> (pass on, deliver) is the technical term for the transmission of tradition: 1 Cor 11:2 ('maintain the traditions even as I delivered them to you'); 15:3 ('I delivered to you as of first importance what I also received'); Jude 3 ('the faith that was once for all delivered to the saints'). The 'sacred command' is probably the apostolic gospel as a whole, delivered as a binding deposit. The language of apostasy from the <em>paradosis</em> is the language of covenant breach: these teachers have not merely changed their minds but repudiated the covenant transmission through which they received their identity.</p>",

    "22": "<p>'A dog returns to its vomit' (Prov 26:11 LXX) and 'a sow that is washed returns to her wallowing in the mud' — Peter combines a biblical proverb (Prov 26:11) with what appears to be a folk proverb not found in the OT. Both animals were symbolically impure in the Jewish purity system, and 'dog' was used as a term of social contempt (Matt 7:6; Phil 3:2; Rev 22:15). The rhetorical force is double: the false teachers have returned to their pre-conversion condition (like a dog or pig returning to its natural behavior), and they have identified themselves as the unclean animals that Jewish law prohibited. In the honor-shame register of the ancient world, the comparison is maximally shaming.</p>"
  },

  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The explicit reference to a second letter connects 2 Peter with 1 Peter — the community addressed is the same diaspora churches of Pontus, Galatia, Cappadocia, Asia, and Bithynia (1 Pet 1:1). 'As reminders to stimulate you to wholesome thinking' (<em>dianoia eilikrinēs</em>): <em>eilikrinēs</em> (sincere, pure, lit. 'judged by sunlight,' the practice of holding pottery to sunlight to detect cracks) describes a mind whose judgment is uncontaminated by the self-interested distortions of the false teachers. The reminder-function of the letter is the testamentary agenda established in ch. 1 (vv. 12-15): Peter writes to ensure the community can remember his teaching after he is gone.</p>",

    "2": "<p>'Recall the words spoken in the past by the holy prophets and the command given by our Lord and Savior through your apostles' — the two-source authority structure (prophets and apostles) is the standard early Christian hermeneutic (Eph 2:20: 'built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets'; Rev 18:20). By identifying both sources explicitly, Peter positions his letter within the authoritative tradition rather than as a novel teaching. The 'command through your apostles' is the <em>entolē</em> of 2:21 — the delivered sacred command. The appeal to both prophetic Scripture and apostolic witness as a unified testimony against the false teachers parallels Paul's double appeal to Scripture and eyewitness tradition in 1 Cor 15:1-11.</p>",

    "3": "<p>The 'scoffers' who mock the parousia promise ('Where is the promise of his coming? For ever since the fathers fell asleep, all things are continuing as they were from the beginning', vv. 3-4) reflect an Epicurean-style skepticism about divine intervention in the regularities of nature: if God were going to act, why hasn't he? The Epicurean doctrine of <em>ataraxia</em> (undisturbed natural regularity, governed by atoms, not divine providence) provided intellectual cover for dismissing apocalyptic expectations. Peter's response: the uniformitarians forget that the past was not uniform — the flood was God's catastrophic intervention in the 'natural order' (vv. 5-6), and the coming fire will be the next. The argument uses Genesis to rebut Epicurean naturalism.</p>",

    "4": "<p>'Ever since our ancestors died, everything goes on as it has since the beginning of creation' — the scoffers' argument is a form of <em>uniformitarianism</em>: the regularity of natural processes disproves the possibility of eschatological intervention. The 'ancestors' (<em>pateres</em>) are probably both the OT patriarchs and the first generation of Christians, whose deaths without the Parousia is read as disconfirming evidence. This argument was real in the early church: 1 Thess 4:13-18, 1 Cor 15, and 2 Thess 2 all address anxiety about deaths occurring before the expected return. The scoffers here use the delay as ammunition for rejecting the Parousia entirely.</p>",

    "5": "<p>'By God's word the heavens came into being and the earth was formed out of water and by water' — the creation by word (<em>theou logō</em>) invokes Gen 1 ('God said... and it was so'). 'Out of water and by water' (<em>ex hydatos kai di' hydatos</em>) reflects Gen 1:2 (the <em>tōhû vābōhû</em> over which the Spirit moved, understood as a watery chaos) and possibly the cosmological tradition of Thales (water as the <em>archē</em>, the primary principle of the cosmos) — though more likely it reflects the Gen 1 reading tradition of Second Temple Judaism. The point is that the same divine word that created the world by ordering primordial water also unraveled that order in the flood (vv. 5-6) and will again unravel it by fire (v. 7).</p>",

    "6": "<p>'By these waters also the world of that time was deluged and destroyed' — the flood as cosmic destruction and re-creation (not merely regional disaster) was a widespread reading in Second Temple Judaism. 1 Enoch 10-11 describes the flood as the purging of the Watcher-pollution from the earth; 4Q252 (Qumran Genesis Pesher) reads the flood as the reversal and renewal of creation. Peter uses the flood as a type of eschatological dissolution: as the primordial waters destroyed the first world-order, the coming fire will dissolve the current world-order in preparation for 'a new heaven and a new earth' (v. 13). The flood and the fire are two acts of the same divine creative-destructive word.</p>",

    "7": "<p>'By the same word the present heavens and earth are reserved for fire' — the eschatological destruction of the cosmos by fire (<em>pyrōsis</em>) was a Stoic cosmological doctrine (<em>ekpyrōsis</em>: periodic cosmic conflagration followed by renewal — <em>palingenesia</em>). Peter likely appropriates the Stoic vocabulary his readers knew while redirecting it: the fire is not the cyclic Stoic conflagration but the singular divine judgment-fire of the Day of the Lord (Isa 66:15-16; Mal 4:1; Zeph 1:18; 3:8). The Stoic audience would recognize the framework; the content — judgment, not mere natural cycle — is distinctly Jewish-Christian. The 'reservation for fire' (<em>tethēsaurismenoi</em>, treasured up) is a dramatic irony: the scoffers who trust in the world's permanence are unknowingly living in a reserved combustion.</p>",

    "8": "<p>'With the Lord a day is like a thousand years, and a thousand years are like a day' — a near-quotation of Ps 90:4 ('a thousand years in your sight are like a day that has just gone by, or like a watch in the night'). Ps 90 is Moses's prayer meditating on divine eternity against human transience: YHWH's timescale is incommensurable with human calculation. The Rabbis later used this verse to calculate that a 'day of God' equals a thousand years, deriving a 6,000-year world-week followed by a messianic Sabbath. 2 Peter uses Ps 90:4 not for chronological calculation but for epistemological humility: human impatience about the Parousia reflects the wrong temporal framework. The Lord is not on human time.</p>",

    "9": "<p>'The Lord is not slow in keeping his promise, as some understand slowness. Instead he is patient, not wanting anyone to perish' — the character of God as patient (<em>makrothymei</em>, long-tempered) and unwilling for any to perish reflects the prophetic portrait of divine compassion that delays judgment for repentance. Ezek 18:23 ('Do I take any pleasure in the death of the wicked? Rather, am I not pleased when they turn from their ways and live?') and Ezek 33:11 express the same divine will. The delay of the Parousia is reframed as divine mercy, not divine indifference or weakness — the same argument Paul makes in Rom 2:4 ('do you presume on the riches of his kindness and forbearance and patience, not knowing that God's kindness is meant to lead you to repentance?').</p>",

    "10": "<p>'The day of the Lord will come like a thief' — the thief-in-the-night image for the sudden and unexpected arrival of the Day of the Lord appears in Jesus's teaching (Matt 24:43-44; Luke 12:39-40), Paul (1 Thess 5:2-4), and Revelation (3:3; 16:15). It derives from the OT Day of the Lord tradition (Joel 2:9; Amos 5:18-20; Zeph 1:14-16) where YHWH comes in sudden judgment. 'The elements will be destroyed by fire' (<em>stoicheia kausoumena lysontai</em>): <em>stoicheia</em> can mean heavenly bodies (Gal 4:3, 9; Col 2:8) or the basic physical components of matter — both traditions support eschatological dissolution.</p>",

    "11": "<p>'What kind of people ought you to be? You ought to live holy and godly lives' — the standard Jewish-Hellenistic <em>diatribe</em> (dialogical preaching form) moves from cosmological assertion to ethical exhortation via rhetorical question. Stoic and Cynic teachers regularly used the question 'what manner of life?' as a transitional device in their discourses on cosmic themes. Peter uses the Stoic-cosmological language of the letter's argument to arrive at the Jewish-covenantal ethical imperative: the impermanence of the present cosmic order creates urgency for holy living, not (as the false teachers imply) freedom from moral constraint. The coming dissolution validates the ethics of the community, not its abandonment.</p>",

    "12": "<p>'Speed its coming' (<em>speudein tēn parousian</em>) — the idea that human repentance or prayer could hasten the coming of the eschatological age was present in early rabbinic tradition (b. Sanhedrin 97b: 'If Israel repented for one day, the son of David would come'; Elijah's task of hastening the age). The concept also appears in Acts 3:19-21 (Peter's speech: 'Repent... so that times of refreshing may come from the Lord'). Whether 2 Peter means that the community's holiness actively accelerates the eschaton or simply that 'looking forward' with active anticipation rather than passive waiting is the right posture is debated, but the tradition of human moral agency affecting the divine timetable was real in Second Temple Judaism.</p>",

    "13": "<p>'A new heaven and a new earth, where righteousness dwells' — the new creation language comes from Isa 65:17 ('See, I will create new heavens and a new earth. The former things will not be remembered, nor will they come to mind') and Isa 66:22. In Second Temple Judaism this became the standard expectation of the post-judgment age: 1 Enoch 45:4-5, 4 Ezra 7:75, 2 Bar. 32:6, and Revelation 21:1 all draw on Isaiah's vision. 'Where righteousness dwells' (<em>dikaiosynē katoikei</em>): the personification of righteousness as an inhabitant of the new creation echoes Isa 32:16-17 and reflects the apocalyptic tradition of the present age as one where unrighteousness dominates and the new age is characterized by the permanent reign of justice.</p>",

    "14": "<p>'Make every effort to be found spotless, blameless and at peace with him' (<em>aspiloi kai amōmētoi</em>) — the language of 'spotless and blameless' is the vocabulary of sacrificial and priestly purity (Num 19:2; Heb 9:14: 'how much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God, purify our conscience'). The community is called to embody the purity of the offering — their lives are a form of priestly presentation to God. 'At peace with him' (<em>en eirēnē</em>) adds the covenant-shalom dimension: the relational wholeness that the covenantal relationship with God entails, the opposite of the hostility that false teaching creates.</p>",

    "15": "<p>'Our Lord's patience means salvation, just as our dear brother Paul also wrote you with the wisdom that God gave him' — the reference to Paul's letters as Scripture in v. 16 is here prefaced by the citation of Paul as an ally on the patience-as-salvation theme. Paul wrote about divine patience in Rom 2:4-5 and 9:22-23 in exactly the terms Peter invokes. The fraternal term 'dear brother' (<em>agapētos adelphos</em>) signals that Peter and Paul stand in the same apostolic tradition, directly countering any suggestion that Petrine and Pauline Christianity were in tension. The historical background of Gal 2:11-14 (Peter and Paul's Antioch confrontation) makes this reconciling reference theologically loaded.</p>",

    "16": "<p>'His letters contain some things that are hard to understand, which ignorant and unstable people distort, as they do the other Scriptures' (<em>hōs kai tas loipas graphas</em>) — this is the earliest explicit reference to Paul's letters as 'Scriptures' (<em>graphai</em>) on a par with the OT. The canonical implications are enormous: by the time 2 Peter was written, Paul's letters were being read in the same hermeneutical framework as the Hebrew Scriptures and subjected to the same kind of interpretive distortion. The 'hard to understand' (<em>dysnoēta</em>) acknowledges the genuine difficulty of Pauline theology (particularly in Romans, where Paul's nuanced treatment of law and grace was being misread in antinomian directions — cf. Rom 6:1: 'Shall we go on sinning so that grace may increase?').</p>",

    "17": "<p>'Since you have been forewarned, be on your guard so that you may not be carried away by the error of the lawless and fall from your secure position' — the community's 'secure position' (<em>stereōmatos</em>) invokes the image of a military fortification. The false teachers threaten to carry the community away (<em>synapachthentes</em>: carried off as spoil of war). This military-security imagery is consistent with the letter's concern for community cohesion against external threat. The 'forewarned' (<em>proginōskontes</em>) positions the community as having an epistemic advantage: the letter itself is the forewarning, and knowing the pattern of false teaching is the community's defensive resource.</p>",

    "18": "<p>'But grow in the grace and knowledge of our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ' — the closing exhortation returns to the <em>epignōsis</em> theme with which the letter opened (1:2-3). The community's defense against false teaching is not primarily argumentative but formational: growth in the genuine knowledge of Jesus Christ. This echoes the letter's opening claim that divine power operates 'through our knowledge of him who called us' (1:3) — the knowledge that enables godliness and equips the community to resist the corrupting influence of those whose knowledge is false. 'To him be glory both now and forever' closes the letter with a doxology that liturgically reinforces the letter's core claim: Jesus Christ, not the false teachers, is worthy of glory.</p>"
  }
}

