TWOJOHN_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>2 John is addressed from 'the elder' to 'the elect lady and her children' — most likely a metaphor for a particular congregation and its members (cf. 1 Pet 5:13 where 'Babylon' = Rome; 'she' = the church in Babylon). The 'elder' is commonly identified with John the Apostle or John the Elder of Ephesus (Papias distinguishes these; Eusebius records the tradition of two Johns in Asia). The letter is a brief (13 verses) traveling advisory: the practice of Greco-Roman hospitality created real danger for Christian communities — traveling teachers could exploit the obligation of hospitality to spread heresy. 2 John's 'do not receive him into your house' (v. 10) restricts the normal hospitality-obligation for doctrinal cause.</p>",

    "2": "<p>'Because of the truth, which lives in us and will be with us forever' — in the Johannine tradition, truth (<em>alētheia</em>) is not an abstract epistemological category but the personal reality of Jesus Christ himself ('I am the way and the truth and the life,' John 14:6) mediated through the Spirit ('the Spirit of truth,' John 14:17; 16:13). The claim that truth 'lives in us' (<em>menousan en hēmin</em>) uses the distinctively Johannine <em>menō</em> (abide, remain) — the same verb used in John 15 for the vine-and-branches union. Truth is not a proposition held but a reality dwelling in the community that constitutes its identity.</p>",

    "3": "<p>'Grace, mercy, and peace from God the Father and from Jesus Christ, the Father's Son' — the threefold greeting formula (grace, mercy, peace) is expanded from Paul's standard 'grace and peace.' In Second Temple Jewish letters, <em>shalom</em> (peace) was the standard greeting; the addition of grace (<em>charis</em>) was a Christian innovation. The identification of Jesus Christ as 'the Father's Son' (<em>tou patros huiou</em>) is a direct anticipation of the doctrinal concern of vv. 7-9: the letter's crisis is precisely over the identity of Jesus as the Son of the Father in bodily reality.</p>",

    "4": "<p>'Walking in truth' (<em>peripatountas en alētheia</em>) — the walking-metaphor for covenant conduct is rooted in the Hebrew <em>halakah</em> tradition: the way one walks (<em>halak</em>) is the totality of one's covenant life, including ethical practice and liturgical observance. The Qumran community similarly spoke of 'walking perfectly in all his commandments' (1QS 1:8). In the Johannine letters, walking in truth versus walking in darkness is the fundamental anthropological and ecclesiological divide: those who walk in truth are those in whom the truth (Christ) abides. 'As the Father commanded us' frames truth-walking as covenant obedience, not philosophical achievement.</p>",

    "5": "<p>'I am not writing you a new command but one we have had from the beginning. I ask that we love one another' — the appeal to 'the beginning' (<em>ap' archēs</em>) recurs throughout the Johannine letters (1 John 1:1; 2:7, 13, 14, 24; 3:8, 11) as a marker of the founding apostolic tradition. In the context of traveling teachers claiming new revelations and new teachings, the appeal to what was known 'from the beginning' is a stability-marker: the community's identity is not defined by progressive revelation from itinerant prophets but by the original witness of the eyewitnesses. The 'new commandment' (John 13:34) was already ancient — it goes back to the night of the Last Supper.</p>",

    "6": "<p>'This is love: that we walk in obedience to his commands. As you have heard from the beginning, his command is that you walk in love' — the mutual definition of love and commandment-keeping is characteristic of the Johannine tradition (John 14:15: 'If you love me, keep my commands'; 1 John 5:3: 'love for God means keeping his commands'). The circular structure (love is obedience; the command is love) reflects the covenantal framework: covenant relationship produces covenant obligation, and the obligation is a form of the relationship. The Deuteronomic background (Deut 6:5; 7:9: 'know therefore that the LORD your God is God, keeping covenant and steadfast love with those who love him and keep his commandments') is the soil of the Johannine ethics.</p>",

    "7": "<p>'Many deceivers, who do not acknowledge Jesus Christ as coming in the flesh, have gone out into the world' — the departure formula 'gone out into the world' (<em>exēlthon eis ton kosmon</em>) mirrors 1 John 4:1 ('many false prophets have gone out into the world') and 1 John 2:19 ('they went out from us'). The theological issue — denial of the bodily reality of Jesus Christ — is the classic Docetic position: Christ only appeared to be bodily human (<em>dokein</em>, to seem). In the context of Hellenistic dualism, which regarded matter as corrupt and spirit as pure, an fully incarnate divine savior was philosophically offensive. The Docetic teachers may have represented an early form of what Ignatius of Antioch would combat a generation later (Ign. Smyrn. 1-7).</p>",

    "8": "<p>'Watch out that you do not lose what we have worked for, but that you may be rewarded fully' — the reward-language (<em>misthon plērē labēte</em>, receive a full wage) belongs to the day-laborer metaphor common in Jewish and early Christian teaching (Matt 20:8-10; 1 Cor 3:14). In the patronage culture of the Roman world, reward (pay) for work done was a normal category for eschatological recompense (cf. Rev 11:18; 22:12). The specific warning against 'losing what was worked for' implies that false teaching can not only add error but subtract the reward that faithful labor would have earned — a concern for what modern readers might call apostasy or syncretism.</p>",

    "9": "<p>'Anyone who runs ahead and does not continue in the teaching of Christ does not have God; whoever continues in the teaching has both the Father and the Son' — 'runs ahead' (<em>proagōn</em>: advances beyond, goes in front) may be a pointed use of the false teachers' self-description: those who claimed to be <em>progressing</em> beyond the basic apostolic teaching into more advanced spiritual knowledge. Gnostic movements typically offered progressive initiatory access to higher revelations. John's counter-claim: advancing beyond the teaching of Christ is not progress but loss — you lose God. Continuing (<em>menōn</em>, abiding) in the foundational teaching is the condition for having both Father and Son.</p>",

    "10": "<p>'If anyone comes to you and does not bring this teaching, do not take them into your house or welcome them' — this instruction radically inverts the normal obligations of Greco-Roman hospitality. In the ancient Mediterranean world, hospitality to travelers was a sacred duty (Heb 13:2: 'do not forget to show hospitality to strangers, for by so doing some people have shown hospitality to angels without knowing it'). Refusing hospitality was a grave social offense. For John to command refusal of hospitality to false teachers signals that the doctrinal stakes override even the foundational social obligation. The house-church setting makes this especially significant: 'your house' is likely the gathering-place of the congregation, not just a private residence.</p>",

    "11": "<p>'Anyone who welcomes them shares in their wicked work' — the sharing-in-evil principle (<em>koinōnei tois ergois autou tois ponērois</em>) reflects the ancient concept of communal moral responsibility. In Roman law, harboring a criminal created legal liability; in Jewish moral tradition, one who enables wrongdoing bears guilt alongside the wrongdoer (Lev 5:1: failure to testify brings guilt; the Rabbinic principle of <em>lifnei iver</em>, not putting a stumbling block before the blind). The hospitality refused in v. 10 is not mere domestic comfort — it is the organizational support (housing, food, introduction to the congregation) that would enable the false teacher to spread the destructive teaching to others.</p>",

    "12": "<p>'I do not want to use paper and ink. Instead, I hope to visit you and talk with you face to face' (<em>stoma pros stoma</em>, lit. mouth to mouth) — the preference for face-to-face over written communication is a standard convention in Greco-Roman epistolary theory. Cicero, Seneca, and Pliny all express the view that letters are an inferior substitute for personal presence; the best communication is direct speech. The phrase <em>stoma pros stoma</em> (mouth to mouth) echoes the description of YHWH's direct speech with Moses in Num 12:8 ('With him I speak face to face, clearly and not in riddles') — a possible subliminal claim for the elder's apostolic authority: as Moses spoke mouth to mouth with God, the elder speaks mouth to mouth with the congregation.</p>",

    "13": "<p>'The children of your sister, who is chosen by God, send their greetings' — the closing greeting from 'the children of your elect sister' extends the household-church metaphor consistently through to the end: the sending church and the receiving church are sister-congregations, both 'chosen' (<em>eklektēs</em>), both part of the single family of God. The closing parallels 1 Pet 5:13 ('She who is in Babylon, chosen together with you, sends you her greetings') where the church greets the church using feminine personification. The brevity of the letter (13 verses, one of the shortest in the NT) confirms its function as a covering note accompanying either oral messengers or written material to a specific congregation.</p>"
  }
}

